Project Python Foundations: FoodHub Data Analysis¶

Marks: 60

Context¶

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective¶

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary¶

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

Question 13: The company wants to provide a promotional offer in the advertisement of the restaurants. The condition to get the offer is that the restaurants must have a rating count of more than 50 and the average rating should be greater than 4. Find the restaurants fulfilling the criteria to get the promotional offer. [3 marks]¶

In [140]:
df['rating'] = df['rating'].replace('Not given', np.nan) #to replace all the not given string with nan (this to change the entire column to float in the next line)
df['rating'] = df['rating'].astype(float) #this is to change the type from string to float in order to calculate mean and count
rating_total = df.groupby('restaurant_name')['rating'].agg(['count', 'mean']).reset_index() #since the promotion only shows the average rating provided, there will be no need to use the ratings that had no rating (this will prevent the missing numbers from affecting the mean)
restaurants_over_50 = rating_total[(rating_total['count'] > 50) & (rating_total['mean'] > 4)] #the conditions that needs to be met
qualified = restaurants_over_50.sort_values(by=['count', 'mean'], ascending=[False, False]) #sort by the order of count, then by mean
qualified['mean'] = qualified['mean'].round(2)
qualified = qualified.reset_index(drop=True)  # Reset existing index so the restaurant name number isn't shown (may confuse someone from understanding)
qualified.index = qualified.index + 1 #to rename the index from 0 to 1
qualified[['restaurant_name', 'count','mean']] #print the output

In [141]:
def charges(cost_of_the_order): #to create a function that calculates based on condition
    if cost_of_the_order > 20: #for orders that are more than $20
        return cost_of_the_order * 0.25 #25% is applied
    elif cost_of_the_order > 5: #for orders that are more than $5 but lower than $20
        return cost_of_the_order * 0.15 #15% is applied
    else: #anything that is lower than or equal to $5
        return 0 #there is no effect on the prices
df['charges'] = df['cost_of_the_order'].apply(charges) # to apply the function to the cost of the order column
net_revenue = df['charges'].sum() #to calculate the net revenue of all orders
print("The net revenue generated by FoodHub is $" + str(round(net_revenue, 2)) + ".")

The net revenue generated by FoodHub is $6166.3.

Observations: FoodHub's net revenue is $6166.30.¶

Conclusion and Recommendations¶

Question 17: What are your conclusions from the analysis? What recommendations would you like to share to help improve the business? (You can use cuisine type and feedback ratings to drive your business recommendations.) [6 marks]¶

Conclusions:¶

  • There were 736 orders that had no ratings.
  • Vietnamese cuisine was the least ordered cuisine type overall.
  • Only four restaurants qualified for the promotional discounted ads.
  • The top five customer had more than seven orders.
  • More people ordered on the weekend compared to the weekday.
  • Average delivery time increased on the weekend compared to the weekday.

Recommendations:¶

  • Knowing that not many people rate food, I would offer promotions (ex: 5-10% discount for subsequent orders) for people to rate food (e.g. creating a star review system) to drive up FoodHub customer users.
  • Since Vietnamese cuisine has low popularity but consistent time frame for delivery, I would incentivize people to order Vietnamese cuisine through promotional coupons (offers other options for users to try new things). This increases net revenue for FoodHub due to increased customer traffic for the restaurant.
  • For restaurants struggling to get their name out to New York customers (only 4 restaurants qualified for discounted ads), encourage restaurant customers to leave reviews to ensure discount eligibility for restaurants running their ads on FoodHub.
  • Create a reward system (e.g. every 2000 points = 20% off or free appetizer) where more orders raises the discount/free food they can get (increase users and profit for FoodHub).
  • Seeing huge disparities in the delivery time, I would suggest hiring more drivers to decrease delivery time or to offer discounts on any orders that are higher than 25 minutes (improves customer's experience while keeping drivers accountable for getting deliveries done on time).
